===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
[[File:Shang bronze script Geng Bing combined.svg|thumb|right|Late Shang bronze script clan insignia forms of {{l|zh|𫷻}}, composed of {{l|zh|庚}} and {{l|zh|丙}}.]]
Various theories:
* {{liushu|p}} – shoulders (''{{w|Shuowen}}'').
* {{liushu|p}} – the tail of a fish (''{{w|Erya}}''). See also [[再]].
* {{liushu|p}} - part of a chariot, as seen in the original form of [[更]].
* {{liushu|p}} – pedestal.
* {{liushu|p}} – small table.
* Original form of {{och-l|柄}}.

Whatever its original sense may be, it has been lost and replaced by its early use as a [[heavenly stem]]. See also the original version of [[更]] (< [[㪅]]).

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014)}} note the phonological relationship between {{och-l|丙|tr=*praŋʔ}} and {{och-l|兩|tr=*p.raŋʔ|a pair}}; how these two are graphically related is noted in {{zh-ref|Baxter (1992)}}. {{zh-ref|Smith (2011)}} suggests that these two words are not only phonologically similar but also etymologically related, with {{zh-l|*丙|couplet, bivalve}} referring to an asterism.

